&lt;h3&gt;Shabbat Parashat Vayeilech&lt;br /&gt;
	Shabbat Shuva&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;h4&gt;General Notes&lt;/h4&gt;
&lt;p&gt;When reciting every Kaddish, after the word &quot;l&#039;eilah,&quot; we add the word &quot;u&#039;l&#039;eilah&quot;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;When reciting the Amidah, include appropriate additions for Shabbat Shuva.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h4&gt;Shacharit&lt;/h4&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Conclude service with Achat Sha&#039;alti (MT 662)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h4&gt;Shacharit Torah Reading&lt;/h4&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Deuteronomy 31:1-30 (P 1547, RP 1387, WTC 1237)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;7 Aliyot&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h4&gt;Shacharit Haftarah&amp;nbsp;&lt;/h4&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Hosea 14:2-10, Micah 7:18-20, Joel 2:15-27 (P 1634, RP 1436)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h4&gt;Haftarah Notes&lt;/h4&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The name &quot;Shabbat Shuvah&quot; is based on the first word of the reading from Hosea (Some also point to the word &quot;Shuva&quot; [return] and its similarity to the word &quot;teshuva&quot; [repentance], which comes from the same root.). Congregations have different customs regarding the Haftarah on Shabbat Shuvah. Some read all three selections; others recite Hosea and either Joel or Micah (Joel when Shabbat Shuva coincides with Parashat Ha&#039;azinu and Micah when it conincides with Parashat Vayeilech).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h4&gt;Mincha&lt;/h4&gt;
&lt;p&gt;When reciting every Kaddish, after the word &quot;l&#039;eilah,&quot; we add the word &quot;u&#039;l&#039;eilah&quot;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;When reciting the Amidah, include additions for Shabbat Shuva.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h4&gt;Mincha Torah Reading&lt;/h4&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Deuteronomy 32:1-12 (P 1556, RP 1400, WTC 1253)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;3 Aliyot&lt;/p&gt;
